entry.title: [keepalive-migration] Run URLLoaderThrottles from content embedder
entry.content:
When `KeepAliveURLLoader` has to handle redirects, throttles created

by blink [1] are all dropped, but some throttles are necessary.



This CL introduces `ContentBrowserClient::CreateURLLoaderThrottlesForKeepAlive()` and its wrapper, which only adds safe_browsing throttle, variation throttle, and GoogleURL throttle, for the use in KeepAliveURLLoader.



See this section [2] from the design doc for more details, and this thread [3] about the discussion around adding a dedicated `ContentBrowserClient::CreateURLLoaderThrottlesForKeepAlive()`

entry.title: [FilesF2] Add util functions to handle tree naming difference
entry.content:
There are 2 differences between the old tree and the new tree:

1. `insanceof` check against `DirectoryTree/DirectoryItem` won't

work with the new tree, we need to wrap the check into a util

function to make sure it works with both implementations.

2. `selectedItem` property v.s. `focusedItem`: the old tree uses

`selectedItem` property to get the current focused item, which is

quite confusing, that's why the new tree updates the name to

`focusedItem`, we need to create a util function to handle this

difference.



Note: adding `type_name` for DirectoryTree and DirectoryItem to

prevent the usage of `instanceof`, because importing the type

itself might trigger circular import issue.

entry.title: CrOS Settings: Separating first and subsequent lifetime metrics.
entry.content:
Separating "ChromeOS.Settings.NumUniqueSettingsChanged.DeviceLifetime"

into ".FirstWeek" and ".SubsequentWeeks". Assuming that users will change more Settings in the first week to customize their device to their liking, so to understand the data better, we will separate the data into 2 histograms. This will help us understand the true value of how many Settings users will change on average, without the data from the first week skewing the results.



This CL is a follow-up to b/280480850.



BUG=b/281946097

TEST=

Manual:

A)

1. Run ChromeOS with OOBE. Take the onboarding steps.

2. Open Settings.

2. Change a Setting that we are recording the name of, such as

switching the toggle for Do Not Disturb.

3. Close the Settings app, open your browser and search

"chrome://histograms", then find the histogram

"ChromeOS.Settings.NumUniqueSettingsChanged.DeviceLifetime.FirstWeek". There

will be one count added to the respective bucket. The bucket

represents the number of unique changes made over the device's

lifetime.

4. Repeat steps 1-3 with different Settings changed each time. The

histogram will each time record the correct number of accumulated

unique Settings changed.

B)

1. Repeat 'A' after a week time has passed.

2. The corresponding histogram will now be called

"ChromeOS.Settings.NumUniqueSettingsChanged.DeviceLifetime.SunsequentWeeks"

NOTE: The recorded count has now been reset, meaning that if we repeat `Do not disturb` toggle

flip after the first week, we will now record it again in

histogram ".SubsequentWeeks".

3. No data will be added to ".FirstWeek" after the first week has

passed.



--gtest_filter="*SettingsUserActionTrackerTest*"



Unittest: DISPLAY=:20 out/Default/unit_tests

entry.title: [css-flex] Try a more conservative intrinsic sizing algorithm
entry.content:
Our first attempt at a better algorithm was not compatible with the web.

This version gives behavior closer to what is currently shipping in all

browsers.



The difference in this version affects only single-line row containers'

min-content sizes. For such containers where no items are growing from

their flex basis to their desired min contribution, an item's final

contribution to the container's min-content size is (1) its flex-basis

if the item has a 0 flex factor in whichever direction it wants to go

(shrink if flex-basis > min-content contribution, grow otherwise);

otherwise: (2) its min-content contribution.



This will probably only be enabled for a few days, but will give us good

compat data even so.

entry.title: Remove the version in android_toolchain CIPD path
entry.content:
Including the toolchain version in the CIPD package path means that

downstream rollers observe major revision changes to the NDK as

completely new CIPD packages, e.g.



chromium/third_party/android_toolchain/r23c/android_toolchain

chromium/third_party/android_toolchain/r25c/android_toolchain



This would result in every downstream repository observing a roller

breakage on every such update, which is undesirable. Consolidate the

toolchain path to always exist at:



chromium/third_party/android_toolchain/android_toolchain



So that only the 'version' attribute of the package is updated and

rollers can update the package without gardener intervention.

entry.title: [PDF OCR] Maybe create OCR service during PdfAccessibilityTree CTOR
entry.content:
Create `ocr_service_` if it's not created but AXMode has `kPDFOcr` for

PDF OCR when `PdfAccessibilityTree` is being created.



When the PDF OCR pref is set, AXMode gets set for PDF OCR and sent to

PDF renderer during its `WebContents` creation. `PdfAccessibilityTree`

then receives this AXMode in `AccessibilityModeChanged()` and creates

`ocr_service_`. However, it's possible that `PdfAccessibilityTree`

starts observing for AXMode through `content::RenderFrameObserver`

after the browser sent AXMode to PDF renderer due to a timing issue.

This CL implements a workaround fix for this timing issue.

entry.title: QsRevamp: Position popup notification on top of shelf-cornered bubbles
entry.content:
When the shelf-cornered bubble is open, popup notification should be

displayed on top of that bubble. In order to do this, we need to make a

lot of changes in multiple parts of the system. This includes:

- Added a param to define which tray bubble is anchored to the corner of

the shelf. Currently, these bubbles are QS, notification tray, tote

and phone hub.

- Added new observers to SystemTrayObserver, notifying when the tray

bubbles changes their visibility and bounds. The popup collection will

receive this signal and adjust the baseline of the popups accordingly.

- Made changes to TrayEventFilter to not close the bubble when user

interact with the popup notification. Similar changes needed to be

made in TrayBubbleWrapper and UnifiedSystemTrayBubble.



Future CLs will take care the z-order of the popup vs tray bubbles,

updating the UI when the popup collection change its height, and handle

all the other edge cases.

entry.title: Extend period identified as printing content analysis
entry.content:
PrintViewManagerBase and PrintViewManager use a state variable to know

when the document is being checked for content analysis. This state

has been set only around the time when a snapshot is being collected,

but has not been including the time for the actual composition and

analysis. This interfered with the out-of-process print drivers

feature logic, resulting in crashes when both features are being used

because a Print Backend service client would unregister prematurely.



Modify the content analysis state to track the entire time that the

document is being checked, resetting it only once an accept/reject

decision has been made. Update the name of this state variable to

better reflect this new approach. This allows PrintViewManagerBase to

check the state in some extra places and ensure that Print Backend

client registration persists while content analysis is still in

progress.



Also add some extra detail to the logging statement in

PrintBackendServiceManager::RegisterClient(), which was helpful to

understand how this problem was occurring.



This allows content analysis browser tests to now complete the printing

sequence without crashing for both in-browser and OOPPD configurations.

entry.title: Reland "Fenced frames: Local network access."
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit c02af164b8b7cee63e3c97901113c386f9100e67



Previous submit caused test timeout for the two new tests:

1. fenced-frame-subresource-fetch.tentative.https.window.js

2. fenced-frame.tentative.https.window.js



For fenced frames, we obtain messages by writing value to/reading

value from a server. This is significantly slower than similar tests

using iframes, because iframes can simply use `window.postMessage()`.



I've specified long timeout for both tests by `// META: timeout=long`.



Otherwise this CL is the same as the original one.



Original change's description:

> Fenced frames: Local network access.

>

> Fenced frames are only allowed in secure context. So the tests are

> all in secure contexts.

>

> 1. Subresource fetch:

>

> Fenced frame's IP address space is set to `kPublic` in order to make

> it subject to local network access check.

>

> web_tests/external/wpt/fetch/local-network-access/

> fetch.https.window.js is replicated and replaced iframes with fenced

> frames. All test cases are passing with the same behaviors as iframes.

>

> 2. Document fetch:

>

> Fenced frame's document fetch initiator can only be the parent.

> Fenced frames can only be navigated in two ways:

>

> 1. Directly by their parent, and never by another frame at a distance

> via `window.location` or `window.open`; in this case the `ClientSecurityState` needs to come from the parent.

> 2. By themselves; in this case the `ClientSecurityState` also needs to

> come from its embedder/parent.

>

> The ClientSecurityState of its parent is supplied to the

> NavigationURLLoader.

> web_tests/external/wpt/fetch/local-network-access/

entry.title: Make sure all HostStatusObservers receive OnClientDisconnected events
entry.content:
This CL fixes an issue where some HostStatusObservers were not receiving

OnClientDisconnected events when an It2Me session was terminated. The

root cause is that the It2MeHost registers itself as a

HostStatusObserver and is the first in a chain of observers. When the

P2P connection is terminated, there are two codepaths:

1.) It2MeHost unregisters itself as an observer and then deletes the

ChromotingHost object

2.) The ChromotingHost notifies observers that the client disconnected



Everything works fine in scenario #1 however for #2, the It2MeHost

receives the OnClientDisconnected notification and then deletes the

ChromotingHost which also causes the destruction of the other observers.



This is a no-no per the contract in host_status_observer.h as the events

are meant to be informational only. I read that as the receiver of the

event can take an asynchronous action but can't tear things down while

it is handling the event.



Thus this CL posts the 'DisconnectOnNetworkThread' call so that tearing

the ChromotingHost occurs outside of the observer notification loop and

all observers now get a chance to handle the event.

entry.title: [Extensions] Fix a UAF issue in WebstoreInstaller.
entry.content:
WebstoreInstaller can invoke a dangling pointer to its

WebstoreInstaller::Delegate member because there is no control over

the lifetime of the delegate. See the bug for more information on how

this can be reproduced.



The fix is to break the dependency between the lifetime of

WebstoreInstaller and the delegate by requiring that the delegate be

owned by the WebstoreInstaller instance. The WebstoreInstaller

instance then guarantees that it will call either

WebstoreInstaller::Delegate::OnExtensionInstallSuccess or

WebstoreInstaller::Delegate::OnExtensionInstallFailure only once,

then delete the delegate.



Since the three current uses of the Delegate class all use the same

pattern, this CL creates a utility class that accepts OnceCallback

instances for forwarding the success or failure calls. The classes

that formerly implemented the Delegate interface can now bind

callbacks that forward to their own member functions when they create

an instance of this class to pass into the WebstoreInstaller

constructor.



In production code, the issue of the guaranteeing the lifetime of the

targets of the callbacks is handled by having the target classes use

a weak pointer when binding their callbacks. This allows

WebstoreInstaller to invoke the callbacks safely through the utility

class even if the target has been destroyed.

entry.title: WebUI: Delete obsolete css_checker.py tool.
entry.content:
The tool has outlived its usefulness.

1) It is implemented using regular expressions.

2) Because of 1, it is hard to support newer CSS features that

introduce new syntax.

3) Warnings coming from css_checker.py have been ignored for a long

time and are often incorrect (for example asking for '0' instead of

'0px' inside calc() statements).

4) The tool is effectively unowned, because it is hard to maintain and

modify.



In the future, we should evaluate and possibly leverage existing open

source tools for the same task.
